{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531783"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:18:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:18:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14628"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14628"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.72,0.09,0.03,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57528"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42987"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40334"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57528"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman is admitted to a hospice with metastatic ovarian cancer. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include paracetamol, ondansetron, and has been started on dexamethasone. She lives alone and has been independent with all personal care. Her main priorities are spending time with family on small outings. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the past two days, she has experienced episodes of confusion, sweating, tremors, and anxiety, which improve after eating. She reports reduced appetite and eight kilograms of weight loss over three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears frail but alert. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 132/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended with shifting dullness. Blood glucose is 2.8 mmol/L (3.9-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular small meals with glucose monitoring","Withhold dexamethasone","Start long-acting insulin","Commence continuous glucose infusion","Commence total parenteral nutrition"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic hypoglycaemia in the context of advanced ovarian cancer. The symptoms of confusion, sweating, tremors, and anxiety that improve with eating are classic features of hypoglycaemia. In patients with advanced cancer, hypoglycaemia can occur due to liver metastases, poor oral intake, or paraneoplastic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular small meals with glucose monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan as it aligns with the patient\u0027s goals of maintaining quality time with family and the ability to communicate. This approach provides a practical and less invasive way to maintain blood glucose levels while respecting the palliative context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous glucose infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly aggressive in this setting and would restrict the patient\u0027s mobility and independence, which are important to her quality of life. A discussion should be held regarding her wishes for intravenous glucose therapy in the future, as it may be beneficial as a short term therapy, especially if she has altered level of conscious state from hypoglycaemia. A plan should also be discussed regarding the role of short acting therapy such as intramuscular glucagon. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting insulin\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this patient has hypoglycaemia, not hyperglycaemia. Insulin would worsen the condition and potentially cause dangerous drops in blood glucose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal parenteral nutrition\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly invasive and inappropriate in this palliative setting where the focus is on comfort and quality of life rather than aggressive nutritional support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithholding dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E would likely worsen the situation as corticosteroids tend to increase blood glucose levels. The dexamethasone may be helping to maintain blood glucose levels and managing other symptoms, including with her metastatic disease. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-diabetic hypoglycaemia in advanced cancer can be caused by liver metastases, poor oral intake, or paraneoplastic effects.","Initial management of hypoglycaemia in palliative care should align with patient goals and preferences, respecting patient autonomy.","Regular small meals and glucose monitoring are important preventive strategies in patients at risk of hypoglycaemia.","Discussion should be held with patients regarding more invasive treatments such as intravenous dextrose infusion or intramuscular glucagon, in treating hypoglycaemia with altered conscious state"],"references":["Kok VC, Lee P-H. Management of Hypoglycemia in Nondiabetic Palliative Care Patients: A Prognosis-Based Approach. Palliative Care: Research and Treatment. 2017;10. doi:10.4137/PCRT.S38956 Available online at ; https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.4137/PCRT.S38956"]},